<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Mayor’s Transport Strategy – Statement of Intent</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:19.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:19.6pt; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Written evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline"> from Campaign for Better Transport (TIC 045)</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Public transport isolation is where the provision of passenger transport modes do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> not sufficiently allow passengers to make the important journeys that are required in modern society. </span></li></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Older people,  job seekers, young people and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> low income groups are particularly likely to experience access difficulties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in isolated areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and also mor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e likely to be dependent on buses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">With the current economic climate a much greater focus must be placed on transport integration rather than competition. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">xamples of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">where integrated Transport can and is working well, such as Network St Albans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (See Parag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">raph 4.4)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">here is still a significantly large part of the population that are being left behind. Those that do not have internet access have little or no links to public transport and are being forced to live in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> social</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> isolation which effects quality of life, local economies and the country as a whole.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Transport Isolation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is on the increase as cuts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to central and local government budgets take place. This is not just a personal issue for the service users but is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">also an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> economic, social and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">environmental</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> issue and the following evidence will highlight the importance of good transport links and what can and is happening to areas with little or no passenger transport provision.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Funding for transport in isolated communities must be ring-fenced. Passenger transport is key to economic recovery and continued investment must be made.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> - why is the issue significant?</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Before responding to the questions posed by the Committ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ee we would make two points.</span></p><p style="line-height:15.4pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15.4pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ocal amenities have been replaced by more centralised units or by more remote</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> development, meaning people are having to travel further.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> This is obviously lin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ked to a rise in car ownership, b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ut a quarter of households in Great</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Britain, for a variet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">y of reasons, do not have a car. </span></p><p style="line-height:15.4pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Isolation is important to define as it is not just people in sparsely populated and rural areas that experience isolation. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Even</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in urban and suburban areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">people may be isolated due to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">poor public t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ransport and lack of many public amenities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We strongly welcome this inquiry. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is evident that Government spending cuts are making the issue of isolation worse as passenger transport has been significantly cut over the last three years. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Campaign for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Better Transport has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> recently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> been working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to highlight the issues passengers face in isolated communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and rural communities in particular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ver the last few months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> we have campaigned</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> for sustained</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> support of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rural transport up to an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d beyond the Spen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ding Round</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We have recently published </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> pieces of research of relevance to the Inquiry</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A literature review on transport and poverty</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Evidence on the transport barriers to getting a job</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Case studies of the social inclusion value of buses</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Crisis of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Bus provision in England</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ul></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All of these studies point towards how important getting public transport right is for low income groups</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All modes of passenger transport are important but it is fair to say the most important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and most frequently used</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> mode of passenger transport in rural areas is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">bus;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> therefore we shall be focusing strongly on buses and their importance throughout this submission of written evidence. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers (e.g. people with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> disabilities, older people, young people) taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The needs of different groups of passengers are only occasionally taken into account when determining the provision of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">public transport to isolated communities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">These groups include: </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Elderly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Passengers</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Younger Passengers</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Unemployed Passengers</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Low Income Passengers</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Disabled Passengers</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Before briefly highlighting the needs of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">different groups of passengers we would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">like to highlight t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">hree points </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">should be taken into account when determining provision of public transport to isolated communities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The importance of public transport to these groups should not be underestimated. Many of the following groups rely on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> public transport to provide access to public services, jobs, education and training.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">National Policy in subsidising public transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">for isolated communities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">needs to be revise as cuts to Local Authority budgets have meant supported bus services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> are being reduced or cut completely, placing many of these vulnerable groups in isolation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Local Policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and planning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> decisions must take into account all user groups such as those with disabilities. Even if public transport exists, unless the relevant pl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">anning to allow access to this transport is provided for many it is useless and will remain in isolation.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The following </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">briefly identifies the needs of user groups that heavily rely on public transport.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Passenger Transport and Isolation for the Elderly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Public t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ransport isolation for the elderly is a very serious issue. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Public t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ransport is a lifeline for many</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">older people, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ith many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">elderly people unable to drive public transport is the only option and for many people over the age of 65 this option is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">not available. Public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ransport for the elderly enables them to connect with them with friends, family and their community whilst allowing them access to health and social care and other key services. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Older people and younger people make more trips by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">passenger</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> transport (bus, coach and rail) than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">any other age group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">his coincides with a decline in the number of people holding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a car driving licence with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">age;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> only 35 per cent of pensioner households in rural areas have no access to a car.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">accessi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">bility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of public transport differs significantly between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">urban and rural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">communities. In urban areas the percentage of people who live within 13 minutes of a regular (hourly) bus is around 95%, in rural areas it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> falls to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">50%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Passenger </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Isolatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">n for the Young</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Young people travel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a shorter total distance and make fewer journeys than they used to but must now make longer journeys to reach their most frequent destinations. They make most of their journeys by car but, in common with older people, they use cars less and travel by bus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">more than people in the middle age groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Young people make significantly fewer car journeys than they did – down from almost 600 trips per person each year in the mid-1990s to 377 trips in 2011 – and fewer young people now own cars or have driving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">licences (only 38% of 17-20 year olds now have a driving license compared to 48% in the early 1990s)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The provision of public transport to compensate for this trend has however not been taken into account by local or central governments. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Isola</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">tion for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">people who are unemployed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The location of job centres causes difficulties for those in rural areas, particularly when Jobcentre Plus offices insist on weekly or daily signing-on and when offices have closed permanently.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Those living in rural ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">eas without access to a car face particular difficulties in finding work due to poor transport provision and a lack of affordable social housing located nearer to employment opportunities. Those on low incomes may also be reluctant to move nearer to jobs d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ue to their informal networks of support or family commitments in the area where they currently live</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Two out of five jobseekers say lack of transport is a barrier to getting a job. The cost of transport can be a problem getting to interviews and transpo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rt problems can be a deterrent to making job applications</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Iso</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">lation for people on low income</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">s – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">People on low incomes face similar issues and obstacles to those who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">are out of work.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Low income families are more dependent than others on bus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">travel; buses account for a larger proportion of their income and the cheaper fare deals which involve paying larger lump sums are often unavailable to them. Bus fare increases restrict the ability of households to meet the transport costs of their childre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">n for important out of school activities and transport costs can be a barrier to employment for low income families</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">People in the lowest income quintile make three times more journeys by bus than people in the highest income quintile</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Transport Isolation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> for people with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Disabled people are more likely to mention transport as a local concern than non-disabled people, 60 per cent of disabled people have no car in the household and hey use buses around 20 per cent more frequently than non-disa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">bled people.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Inaccessible transport cuts disabled people off from community and family life.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Fifty per cent say they did not see friends and family</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">as often as they’d like because of inaccessible transport and 20% find it difficult or impossible to get </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the healthcare they need because of inaccessible transport.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities? How c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">an these challenges be overcome?</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The main challenge to prov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">iding better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities is funding. Since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2010 central Government funding for buses has been cut by 20% and funding for supported bus services has been cut by 20%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Supply and demand is an issue in iso</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">lated communitie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a higher cost per passenger journey for the operators. The wider benefits to local economies must be considered when making decisions on local transport.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Integrated Transport – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Due to the nature of a privatise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> rail network and deregulated bus services a huge challenge is getting transport operators to work together to promote integrated transport, which in isolated communities can be vital. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Network St Albans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">was launched in 2009 to bring together all the orga</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nisations which have a role to play in providing/improving transport in the city of St Albans, with the aim to reduce traffic congestion. It was St Albans Local Strategic Partnership (LSP) that formed the basis for developing a public transport related par</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tnership to come up with alternatives to single occupancy car use in St Albans.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The negative impacts imposed on the city and wider area from local traffic congestion and pollution (specifically on Pea Hen Junction), needed a strategic approach, which in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cludes improving public transport service provision and infrastructure.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Greater integrated transport systems should also be strongly encouraged for isolated areas enabling bus and train operators to work with local authorities to promote cooperation and enabling a greater door to door journey experience from public transport. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A study by the Campaign for Better Transport on door to door journeys identified four key points needed for success</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Providing real time information, adequate signage and mapping between transport modes is vital to the success of integrate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d transport.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The Government should ensure that data on timetabled and real-time public transport operations is freely available for use by third parties, subject to controls on accuracy and quality. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Interchange</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> – Transport interchanges should be focused </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">on the needs of passengers rather than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the transport modes themselves. Network Rail, bus operators and local transport authorities should do more to promote more people-centred design in new transport interchanges, particularly for waiting areas, and to al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">low for pedestrian movement between services and with surrounding streets.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Connections - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Punctuality is important to give passengers confidence that they can make connecting services, whether by train or bus. Passenger Focus, the Office of Rail Regulation and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Traffic Commissioners should continue to focus on punctuality and reliability, bu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t should also support operators keeping connections where appropriate. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Ticketing - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Dutch experience of zonal tickets (and the experience of their introduction in London in the 1980s) shows their potential to simplify ticketing and grow demand. The De</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">partment for Transport should use its smart ticketing programme as an opportunity to work with Transport Authorities and transport operators to introduce a simple, integrated fare structure outside London as a stage to rolling out </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">smart ticketing across th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e country.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengers in isolated communities? How could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Community Transport be improved?</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Community transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a lifeline in both rural and urban areas. It takes disabled people t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">o work, children to school, sick people to healthcare and older people to the shops. It runs local bus routes and provides transport for a wide range of clubs, voluntary bodies and care homes. People shape the services they want and comm</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">unity transport mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">es it happen.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Community Transport schemes serving the most remote corners of the country, or schemes working in partnership with other local services like youth clubs or care homes, can really make a huge difference to people who use them. Community Transport is part of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the Transport mix in isolated communities but not the sole </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">solution to passenger transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Central Government and Local Authorities are unrealistic if they expect volunteer run community transport projects to fill gaps left by deep bus cuts. Research fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">om the Community Transport Association has shown that community transport can only fill between 10 to 15 per cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of former supported transport provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The integration of services and pooling for budgets, at both local and national levels, can ensure t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">hat public money is made to work harder. Some local authorities have already made savings by integrating the way they contract public bus services, school buses and social services transport. Partnerships between councils, operators and big institutions li</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ke hospitals and universities have had good results. Taxi buses, NHS transport, travel schemes for post 16 students and social enterprises all have a part to play. In some cases core routes linking towns are met by demand response village services at reque</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">st stops. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">4.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A ‘Total Transport’ solution for areas affected by cuts to services which would bring together all transport provision in an area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> such as private operators, council run services, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ospital </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ransport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and social services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">4.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Community Rail Partnersh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ips play</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> an important </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">role in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> providing transport for isolated communities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The case for new or reopened connections is increasingly strong, with demand for rail now at its highest level since before the Second World War, despite the network being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">considerably smaller than then. Despite the growing case for these connections, there is no clear process in the rail industry for this to happen and many local authorities lack the capacity or skills to progress schemes themselves. Some new lines and stat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ions have been built, however, and demand on these new lines and stations has usually been higher than forecast.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">difficult to say what extent passengers in isolated communities should rely upon taxis as previously described there are many different service users in these areas that all have di</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">fferent needs and requirements.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">If taxis are used to replace public trans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">port then they should be demand responsive. Can a replacement taxi be adequately used for people in work or education at peak times. How far would this service also booked in advance.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There are various Taxi Voucher Schemes in place across a few </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">places</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">England, most notably in London but also in Surrey, Cheshire, Brighton and Hove for example. Outside London these vouchers amount to around £70 per year on the basis that users give up their National Bus Pass in exchange.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A recent Case Study</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> by Campaign for Better Transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of an area in the North East</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> looked at an housing estate where bus cuts had taken place and where the local council had replaced the supported bus service with a r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">esidual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">free </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">bus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">service to the local supermarket. This st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">udy found that that some residents were forced into taking taxi’s but only those who could afford to. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Local residents were left isolated causing very serious impacts for many such as leaving the house much less to go shopping, visit friends and family. F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">inancial impacts due to having to travel by taxis, and most seriously, health and social impacts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">A lot of older people than me live around here and especially early morning I relied on this bus service. I can't walk very well, I have a stick so walking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> far is not an option unless the weather is dry.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">” (Female, aged 46 to 65, not working and not looking for work, no access to a car, has a disability or ill health)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">6.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Demand responsive transport can be important for residents in isolated communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> In Simo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">n Norton’s evidence to this committee he highlights the guidelines for good </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">demand responsive service, which include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The service should be clearly advertised as being open to all without restriction. Registration, if available, should be voluntary so peo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ple don't have to provide personal information just for a one-off journey. Also, it should be stated clearly whether people who intend to pick a service up at a "compulsory" stop but leave at a demand responsive stop have to book.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Freephone numbers should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> be used for the benefit of people ringing from callboxes.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Same day bookings should be possible, at least for journeys starting after the morning peak. Having to book on a Friday to travel the next Monday is particularly unacceptable.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">challenges associated with funding transport services in isolated communities? How can these services be made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> more affordable?</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Funding transport services in isolated communities is getting progressively harder and harder with spending cuts across the boar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d since 2010. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There must be a greater focus on transport integration and Local Authorities working together with all transport operators. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Different modes of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ransport should be working together not against each other – it should not be a case of bus versus rail. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Whilst many argue for spending cuts to transport across the country</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> there must be a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">general</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> recognition that investing in passenger transport is goo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d for the country with wider benefits experienced economicall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">y, socially and environmentally to having a good transport system. People in isolated communities must not be left behind when budgets are cut and savings are made. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">7.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A way forward would be to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">create a ring fenced fund from Central Government for local buses which would p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ool investment in buses from the Government departments that most benefit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">from them – DWP, DfE, DH. This would be d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">istributed as now through the Bus Service Operators Grant or t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">hrough a new approach that supports buses in rural as well as in urban areas based on accessibility.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">August</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Transport and Poverty: A Literature Review, Campaign for Better Transport, July 2012, </span><a href="http://www.bettertransport.org.uk/files/transport-and-poverty-literature-review.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bettertransport.org.uk/files/transport-and-poverty-literature</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">-review.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Transport barriers to getting a job – Evidence from Citizens Advice clients, Campaign for Better Transport, July 2012, </span><a href="http://www.bettertransport.org.uk/files/Transport-barriers-to-getting-a-job.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bettertransport</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">.org.uk/files/Transport-barriers-to-getting-a-job.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Ar